  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **International Treaties and Conventions:** The Financial Action Task Force on Money Laundering (FATF) is an intergovernmental organization that sets international standards and promotes effective implementation of legal, regulatory and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. Most countries adhere to FATF recommendations and have implemented laws criminalizing money laundering. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime also requires signatory states to criminalize money laundering.\n*   **National Laws:** Almost every country in the world has laws that make money laundering a crime. These laws typically prohibit the concealing or disguising the proceeds of criminal activity, as well as knowingly participating in transactions involving such proceeds.\n*   **Public Policy:** Money laundering facilitates a wide range of criminal activities, including drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and fraud. By making it illegal, governments aim to disrupt these activities and protect the integrity of the financial system.\n*   **Enforcement:** Law enforcement agencies worldwide investigate and prosecute money laundering offenses, demonstrating a commitment to combating this crime.\n*   **Reputational Risk:** Countries that fail to criminalize and effectively combat money laundering risk being blacklisted by international organizations and facing economic sanctions.\n\nWhile specific laws and regulations may vary from country to country, the fundamental principle that money laundering is illegal is universally accepted.",
